<!--
  Cowrie Honeypot — Phase 2 Detection Rules
  honeypot-soc-lab | Author: Seif Allah Nazmy

  Phase 2 rules: campaign-specific attacker behaviors derived from 13 days
  of live honeypot data (2026-05-13 to 2026-05-26, 698,309 events, 2,685
  unique attacker IPs). Each rule targets a concrete IOC or TTP fingerprint
  observed repeatedly in the collected log file.

  Rule ID range: 200005-200011
  Selected to continue Phase 1 range (200001-200004) without conflict.

  MITRE ATT&CK references included per rule.
-->

<group name="cowrie,honeypot,ssh">

  <!-- RULE 200005: SSH Backdoor Key Injection — mdrfckr Botnet
       MITRE: T1098 - Account Manipulation
       Tactic: Persistence | Severity: Critical (level 14)

       Real-world observation:
       extract_ssh_keys.py found a single RSA public key (comment "mdrfckr")
       injected into ~/.ssh/authorized_keys on 6,273 separate occasions across
       1,342 unique source IPs. The command pattern is always:
           echo "ssh-rsa AAAA...== mdrfckr" >> .ssh/authorized_keys
       This establishes a persistent backdoor that survives password changes,
       allowing the operator to re-enter any compromised host at will.
       The scale (>93% of all authorized_keys events use the same key)
       confirms this is a coordinated botnet campaign rather than opportunistic
       access. -->
  <rule id="200005" level="14">
    <decoded_as>json</decoded_as>
    <field name="eventid">cowrie.command.input</field>
    <field name="input" type="pcre2">authorized_keys</field>
    <description>Honeypot: SSH backdoor key injection via authorized_keys — mdrfckr botnet campaign detected.</description>
    <mitre>
      <id>T1098</id>
    </mitre>
    <group>persistence,ssh_key_injection,botnet</group>
  </rule>

  <!-- RULE 200006: Root Password Change via chpasswd
       MITRE: T1136 - Create Account
       Tactic: Persistence | Severity: High (level 13)

       Real-world observation:
       credential_analysis.py identified chpasswd commands among post-login
       activity on sessions that had already injected the mdrfckr key. The
       sequence — inject SSH key, then change root password — is a two-step
       account takeover: the key provides silent re-entry, the password change
       locks out the legitimate owner and any competing attacker who may have
       used the default credentials to gain initial access. -->
  <rule id="200006" level="13">
    <decoded_as>json</decoded_as>
    <field name="eventid">cowrie.command.input</field>
    <field name="input" type="pcre2">chpasswd</field>
    <description>Honeypot: Root password change via chpasswd — account takeover attempt detected.</description>
    <mitre>
      <id>T1136</id>
    </mitre>
    <group>account_takeover,persistence</group>
  </rule>

  <!-- RULE 200007: Cryptominer Dropper bendi.py
       MITRE: T1496 - Resource Hijacking
       Tactic: Impact | Severity: Critical (level 15)

       Real-world observation:
       command_tracker.py surfaced "bendi.py" as a recurring filename in
       post-login command sequences. The script is fetched from an attacker-
       controlled host and executed directly. The naming pattern ("bendi") and
       execution method (curl | python or wget then python bendi.py) match
       documented cryptomining dropper campaigns that deploy XMRig or
       compatible Monero miners on compromised Linux servers. Level 15 is
       assigned because execution of bendi.py indicates the host has already
       been compromised and active resource exfiltration is underway. -->
  <rule id="200007" level="15">
    <decoded_as>json</decoded_as>
    <field name="eventid">cowrie.command.input</field>
    <field name="input" type="pcre2">bendi\.py</field>
    <description>Honeypot: CRITICAL — Cryptominer dropper bendi.py detected — active cryptomining campaign.</description>
    <mitre>
      <id>T1496</id>
    </mitre>
    <group>cryptominer,malware,critical</group>
  </rule>

  <!-- RULE 200008: Competing Malware Killed via pkill
       MITRE: T1562 - Impair Defenses
       Tactic: Defense Evasion | Severity: Medium-High (level 10)

       Real-world observation:
       session_replay.py and command_tracker.py both show pkill appearing in
       automated post-login scripts. Common targets include miner process names,
       other botnet agents, and watchdog daemons. This is characteristic of
       "botnet competition" — each new campaign kills existing malware before
       installing its own payload to claim exclusive use of the host's CPU.
       The presence of pkill in a post-compromise session is therefore a
       reliable signal that an automated infection workflow is executing,
       even when the payload binary name is unknown or obfuscated. -->
  <rule id="200008" level="10">
    <decoded_as>json</decoded_as>
    <field name="eventid">cowrie.command.input</field>
    <field name="input" type="pcre2">pkill</field>
    <description>Honeypot: Competing malware killed via pkill — active botnet competition detected.</description>
    <mitre>
      <id>T1562</id>
    </mitre>
    <group>defense_evasion,botnet</group>
  </rule>

  <!-- RULE 200009: Known Mirai Credential — 345gs5662d34
       MITRE: T1078 - Valid Accounts
       Tactic: Initial Access | Severity: High (level 12)

       Real-world observation:
       credential_analysis.py ranked "345gs5662d34" as the single most common
       password observed in the dataset with 6,146 attempts, followed by
       "3245gs5662d34" with 6,122 attempts. These credential strings are not
       dictionary words; they are default credentials embedded in a specific
       Mirai botnet variant and have appeared in public Mirai source code leaks.
       A successful login using this credential therefore indicates the attacker
       is running Mirai or a derivative — enabling higher-confidence attribution
       and automatic escalation compared to a generic brute-force success alert. -->
  <rule id="200009" level="12">
    <decoded_as>json</decoded_as>
    <field name="eventid">cowrie.login.success</field>
    <field name="username" type="pcre2">345gs5662d34</field>
    <description>Honeypot: Known Mirai botnet credential 345gs5662d34 detected — botnet fingerprint confirmed.</description>
    <mitre>
      <id>T1078</id>
    </mitre>
    <group>botnet,known_malware,mirai</group>
  </rule>

  <!-- ================================================================
       RULE 200010: File Download from Honeypot
       Fires on ANY file download attempt via Cowrie.
       Derived from real observation: attacker at 176.65.139.213
       downloaded Mirai binaries from confirmed C2 server 45.81.234.64
       (armv6l, mips, mipsel, sh4, x86, 10Gbins.sh)

       MITRE: T1105 — Ingress Tool Transfer
       Tactic: Command and Control | Severity: Critical (level 13)

       Note: url field does not support pcre2 in Wazuh.
       Any file download on a honeypot is inherently malicious.
       C2 server 45.81.234.64 confirmed malicious — 11/91 VirusTotal vendors.
  ================================================================ -->
  <rule id="200010" level="13">
    <decoded_as>json</decoded_as>
    <field name="eventid">cowrie.session.file_download</field>
    <description>Honeypot: CRITICAL — File download attempt detected — possible Mirai binary or malware staging from confirmed C2 infrastructure</description>
    <mitre>
      <id>T1105</id>
    </mitre>
    <group>malware,c2,mirai,critical</group>
  </rule>

  <!-- RULE 200011: Go-Based SSH Botnet Scanner — SSH-2.0-Go
       MITRE: T1595 - Active Scanning
       Tactic: Reconnaissance | Severity: Medium (level 11)

       Real-world observation:
       find_client_versions.py showed SSH-2.0-Go as the single most common
       client version string with 62,372 occurrences — representing 66% of all
       version events and far exceeding any legitimate SSH client. The Go SSH
       library (golang.org/x/crypto/ssh) does not set a custom version banner
       by default, so "SSH-2.0-Go" is the literal default string emitted by
       custom-built Go tools such as scanner bots and automated exploit
       frameworks. Notably, extract_ssh_keys.py confirmed that the mdrfckr
       botnet — which performed 6,273 key injections — is primarily driven by
       Go-based tooling, making SSH-2.0-Go an effective campaign fingerprint
       for early detection before any login attempt succeeds. -->
  <rule id="200011" level="11">
    <decoded_as>json</decoded_as>
    <field name="eventid">cowrie.client.version</field>
    <field name="version" type="pcre2">SSH-2\.0-Go</field>
    <description>Honeypot: Go-based SSH botnet scanner detected — mdrfckr campaign fingerprint SSH-2.0-Go identified.</description>
    <mitre>
      <id>T1595</id>
    </mitre>
    <group>reconnaissance,botnet,go_scanner</group>
  </rule>

</group>
